Let $R$ be a commutative ring.
Let $G$ be an $R$-module.
Let $G^*$ be the algebraic dual of $G$.
Let $\innerprod x t$ be the evaluation linear transformation from $G$ to $G^{**}$.
Then the mapping $\phi: G \times G^* \to R$ defined as:
:$\forall \tuple {x, t} \in G \times G^*: \map \phi {x, t} = \innerprod x t$
satisfies the following bilinearity properties:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | n = 1
      | q = \forall x, y \in G: \forall t \in G^*
      | l = \innerprod {x + y} t
      | r = \innerprod x t + \innerprod y t
}}
{{eqn | n = 2
      | q = \forall x \in G: \forall s, t \in G^*
      | l = \innerprod x {s + t}
      | r = \innerprod x s + \innerprod x t
}}
{{eqn | n = 3
      | q = \forall x \in G: \forall t \in G^*: \forall \lambda \in R
      | l = \innerprod {\lambda x} t
      | r = \lambda \innerprod x t
}}
{{eqn | r = \innerprod x {\lambda t}
}}
{{end-eqn}}

